A classic example is **structural mode interaction in flight control systems**: bending vibrations of an airframe or rocket get picked up by inertial sensors (gyros/accelerometers), fed into the autopilot, and the resulting actuator commands excite the same structural mode—closing a positive-feedback loop that diverges (sometimes called aeroservoelastic flutter or control-structure interaction). NASA's early launch vehicles addressed this with notch filters tuned to the bending frequencies; insufficient gain/phase margin at the bending mode caused the Falcon 9 GTO mission anomalies and contributed to early Ariane and N-1 difficulties. The same failure mode appears in hard-disk drive servo loops, where spindle/arm resonances alias into the position-error signal and force notch-filter compensation. In robotics it manifests as limit-cycle "chatter" when a stiff PID loop drives a compliant joint near its resonance. The fix is always frequency-domain: identify the mechanical mode, then add notch filters, roll-off, or reduce loop bandwidth so the controller cannot pump energy into the resonance.
